Our poet made songs which maidens might sing in their rhythmical games,
or as they sat at the grinding-stone. In India the boatman sings as he
rows, the ryot sings as he draws from the well, the sepoy sings on his
march. A feature of such songs is the refrain, which is usually a mere
collection of euphonic syllables, though it may have a meaning. Here are
specimens of a few songs intended for women. The refrain of the first,
"Ēlōrembāvāy" probably means "Receive and ponder what I say, O lady."
The Grinding song, strangely enough, is used at funerals, as also is the
'Antiphony.' The song of 'The Three Castles’ Destruction' is supposed to
accompany play with a ball or a kind of shuttle called 'undī.' For the
legend of the Three Castles, see page [7](htss02.htm#page_7.md). 'The
Shoulder-Play' is for some ancient game in which women grasped each
other's shoulders.

<span id="page_102">p. 102</span> <span id="page_103">p. 103</span>

